SIMPLE: resume
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Resume
<hw>Re*sume"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Resumed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>;<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Resuming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>resumere</ets>,
<ets>resumptum</ets>; pref. <ets>re-</ets> re- + <ets>sumere</ets> to
take: cf. F. <ets>r⟦eacute⟧sumer</ets>. See <er>Assume</er>,
<er>Redeem</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To take back.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The sun, like this, from which our sight we have,⟦br⟧
Gazed on too long, <qex>resumes</qex> the light he gave.</q>
<rj><qau>Denham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Perhaps God will <qex>resume</qex> the blessing he has bestowed
ere he attains the age of manhood.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To enter upon, or take up again.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Reason <qex>resumed</qex> her place, and Passion fled.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To begin again; to recommence, as something which
has been interrupted; <as>as, to <ex>resume</ex> an argument or
discourse</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Resummon</ent>⟦br⟧
